[normal] in issue in 
[normal]Åkerberg
[normal] 
[normal]Fransso
[normal]n
[normal] 
[normal]was itself enacted to implement the VAT directive, but whether it was being used to implement the obligations flowing from the directive, which it clearly w
[normal]as. 
[normal]The contrary conclusion entails the following untenable proposition: the Charter would be triggered if a Member State chose to implement the relevant obligations by, for example, enacting discrete legal provisions dealing with the enforcement obligation solely in relation to the EU VAT directive, but it would not be applicable if the Member State chose to meet the obligations through application of existing enforcement rules to 
[normal]EU 
[normal]VAT, even though the content of the rules is the same. 
[normal]Nor with respect do I agree with the view that the interaction between the national law and EU 
[normal]law 
[normal]was in some way merely incidental
[normal] in 
[normal]Åkerberg
[normal] 
[normal]Fransso
[normal]n
[normal]. VAT is a primary source of EU revenue, and the penalty regime for evasion is therefore central to that revenue base. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]I was asked to consider 
[normal]how extensive 
[normal]are 
[normal]the safeguards in Article 1(2) and 2 of P
[normal]rotocol
[normal] 30
[normal], and to comment on 
[normal]AG 
[normal]Trstenjak's
[normal] analysis of them in 
