[normal]2)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Article 1(2) provides that: 
[normal]‘
[normal]In particular, and for the avoidance of doubt, nothing in Title IV of the Charter creates 
[normal]justiciable
[normal] rights applicable to Poland or the United Kingdom except in so far as Poland or the United Kingdom has provided for such rights in its national law.
[normal]’
[normal] 
[normal]3)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Article 1(2) is clearly worded and serve
[normal]s
[normal] to prevent the creation of 
[normal]justiciable
[normal] rights in relation to Title IV except insofar as Poland and the UK have provided for such rights in national law. 
[normal]The principal qualification to this proposition is that Article 1(2) of Protocol 30 only prevents the creation of such 
[normal]justiciable
[normal] rights insofar as they might otherwise flow from the Charter. It is not a barrier to the creation of such rights insofar as they might be based on 
[normal]another legal 
[normal]ground that is capable of giving rise to rights 
[normal]stricto
[normal] 
[normal]sensu
[normal]. Th
[normal]us, for example, 
[normal]UK 
[normal]workers cannot rely on Article 27 of the Charter to generate rights to information, but this does not preclude such rights flowing from directives 
[normal]insofar as they 
[normal]cover this area (see Charter Explanations, p. 10). The same is true in relation to, for example, Article 30, protection from unjustified dismissal, in the sense that directives have provided such protection in some spheres at least.  
[normal]4)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]AG 
[normal]Trstenjak
[normal] 
[normal]regards 
[normal]Article 1(2) of Protocol 30 
[normal]as 
[normal]reaffirm
[normal]ing
[normal] the principle, set out in Article 51(1) of the Charter, that the Charter does not create 
[normal]justiciable
[normal] rights as between private individuals
[normal], and also believes that it rules out 
[normal]new EU rights and entitlements being derived from Articles 27 to 38 of the Charter of Fundamental 
[normal]Rights, on which those entitled could rely against the United Kingdom or against Poland. 
[normal]The first half of the preceding sentence represents orthodoxy, (the Charter itself does not have horizontal application as between individuals); the second half of the sentence is the most natural legal interpretation of Article 1(2).
[normal]5)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Article 2 states that: ‘
[normal]To the extent that a provision of the Charter refers to national laws and practices, it shall only apply to Poland or the United Kingdom to the extent that the rights or principles that it contains are recognised in the law or practices of Poland or of the United Kingdom.’
[normal] 
[normal]6)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Article 2 
[normal]is
[normal] an important limitation on the application of 
[normal]those
[normal] Charter 
[normal]rights
[normal] 
[normal]that
[normal] 
[normal]make
[normal] 
[normal]reference
[normal] to national 
[normal]laws
[normal] and practices. The Charter 
[normal]is
[normal] 
[normal]ambiguous
[normal] as to 
[normal]whether
[normal] the right 
[normal]asserted
[normal] must 
[normal]be
[normal] 
[normal]recognized
[normal] in the national 
[normal]law
[normal] of the 
[normal]particular
[normal] 
