[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A third issue that I was asked to consider was the likelihood that the Charter might be read so as to establish horizontal rights, given that courts, including national courts, must in accord with Article 51 
[normal]respect the rights, observe the principles and promote the application thereof in accordance with their respective powers
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]I was asked also to consider 
[normal]whether parallels with the effects on the courts of the HRA 
[normal]could 
[normal]be drawn, e.g. in privacy or employment litigation (e.g. 
[normal]Benkharbouche
[normal] v Embassy of Sudan; 
[normal]Janah
[normal] v
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Embassy
[normal] of Libya, 4 October 2013, EAT).
[normal]2)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The horizontality issue is complex as I noted in my earlier submission, and this is borne out by detailed academic study.
[normal] 
[normal] Suffice it to say the following for the present. 
[normal]3)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]First, 
[normal]I think it very unlikely that the CJEU will interpret the Charter so as to render its provisions in general 
[normal]directly 
[normal]applicable as between private parties. There will not in the jargon of the trade be direct horizontality flowing from Charter, whereby individuals could use the Charter as the cause of action so as to impose obligations on other private parties. Such an interpretation does not sit well with the language of Article 51 and it would provoke strong opposition from some national courts. AG 
[normal]Trstenjak
[normal] 
[normal]in 
[normal]NS 
[normal]clearly felt that such direct horizontality was ruled out by Article 51. 
[normal]4)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Secondly, particular Charter rights that correspond with rights found in the Lisbon Treaty may however have horizontal impact,
[normal] 
[normal]in the sense that 
[normal]the 
[normal]relevant 
[normal]Treaty provisions have been interpreted in this way by the CJEU.
[normal]5)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Thirdly
[normal], the issues raised as to whether bills of rights should have direct horizontal impact are themselves complex and I do not explore 
[normal]them 
[normal]further here, other than to say that the arguments against such horizontality are weaker than is commonly perceived. 
[normal]6)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Finally
[normal], 
[normal]some 
[normal]national legal systems do give 
[normal]their 
[normal]national bill of rights some measure of indirect horizontal impact, whereby the rights are used as interpretive devices 
[normal]when construing, for example, private law precepts of contract and tort, or statutes that affect private relations, with the consequence that the interpretation which is most compatible with the relevant constitutional right is preferred.
[normal] 
[normal]It would be difficult for national constitutional courts that employ this strategy to object 
[normal]to its being used by the CJEU. Indirect horizontal effect of this kind fits with the injunction in Article 51 that EU and national institutions, including courts, must ‘
[normal]respect the rights, observe the principles and promote the application thereof in accordance with their respective powers
[normal]’. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The fourth of the additional issues that I was asked to address is concerned with the 
[normal]extent to which the Charter can really be said to be declaratory of pre-existing EU fundamental rights, and how the answer to this issue fits with the injunction in Article 6(1) TEU that the Charter does not extend the competence of the EU as defined in the Treaties.
[normal]2)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Article 51(2) provides that ‘t
[normal]he Charter does not extend the field of application of Union law beyond the powers of the Union or establish any new power or task for the Union, or modify powers and tasks as defined in the Treaties
[normal]’
[normal].
[normal]3)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Charter was self-consciously drafted so as to be declaratory of existing rights, rather than constitutive of new rights. This is reflected in the Preamble, which states that: ‘
[normal]This Charter reaffirms, with due regard for the powers and tasks of the Union and for the principle of subsidiarity, the rights as they result, in particular, from the constitutional traditions and international obligations common to the Member States, the European Convention for the Protection of Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms, the Social Charters adopted by the Union and by the Council of Europe and the case-law of the Court of Justice of the European Union and of the European Court of Human Rights
[normal]’
[normal].
[normal] The Explanations attached to the Charter go to considerable length to explain the provenance of each Charter right by locating it in one of the sources 
[normal]listed in the Preamble. 
[normal]There are three relevant points that should be made about this drafting strategy.
[normal]4)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]First, although each Charter right is duly located in one of the sources listed above the very fact of their inclusion in the Charter
[normal], which has 
[normal]the same status as the TEU and 
[normal]TFEU, 
[normal]gives some rights greater force than they would have had hitherto. Thus, for example, a particular Charter right may be found in an international obligation or in a Social Charter adopted by the EU, but the impact of such a right within the EU and national legal order will be greater by its inclusion in the Charter, which has the same legal status 
[normal]as
[normal] the constituent treaties.  
[normal]5)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Second,
[normal] 
[normal]it is generally accepted that 
[normal]Article 51(2) prohibits construction of the Charter such as to afford new or modified legislative competence to the Union. 
[normal]This 
[normal]does
[normal] not
[normal],
[normal] however
[normal],
[normal] preclude the claim for certain new entitlements
[normal],
[normal] provided that they could be satisfied through the exercise of existing competence. 
[normal]6)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Third, 
[normal]the Charter 
[normal]rights can be used as interpretive devices when construing EU action or Member State action that falls within the scope of EU law, in order to ensure that the relevant provision is given the best possible reading in the light of the applicable Charter right. It is also open to the CJEU to invalidate EU legislative, delegated or implementing acts for failure to comply Charter rights. It is also possible for the CJEU to find pursuant to Article 267 TFEU that Member State action violates EU law for failure to comply with Charter rights. 
